00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.200
Good morning, everyone. Thank you for having me.
I know 8am lectures are — let's say — an acquired taste.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:15.800
Today we're going to talk about artificial intelligence in healthcare.
Not the science fiction version. The real, messy, imperfect version.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.300
I want to start with a question I ask every new cohort at Stanford:
what problem are we actually trying to solve?

00:00:21.500 --> 00:00:27.100
Because AI is not a solution. It's a capability.
And capabilities without clear problem statements are just expensive toys.

00:00:27.300 --> 00:00:33.600
In healthcare, the problem statements are painfully clear.
Clinician burnout. Diagnostic error rates. Unequal access to specialist care.

00:00:33.800 --> 00:00:39.200
Let me give you a number: radiologists review an average of
200 to 300 images per day in a busy hospital.

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:45.100
That's not reading a handful of scans carefully over a coffee.
That's sustained, high-stakes pattern recognition for eight-plus hours.

00:00:45.300 --> 00:00:51.700
Fatigue degrades performance. We know this.
Error rates climb measurably in the final hours of a shift.

00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:57.400
This is where AI offers something genuinely valuable —
not replacing the radiologist, but being the second pair of eyes that never gets tired.

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:03.200
The first clinical AI systems approved by the FDA were narrow.
Very narrow. One model, one task, one imaging modality.

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:09.800
IDx-DR, approved in 2018, detected diabetic retinopathy from retinal photographs.
That was it. Nothing else.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.300
And that narrowness was a feature, not a bug.
You could validate it. You could audit it. You could trust the failure modes.

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:22.900
The field has since moved toward foundation models — large,
general-purpose models pre-trained on massive biomedical datasets.

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:29.400
Med-PaLM, BioGPT, ClinicalBERT — these can handle radiology reports,
clinical notes, genomic data, and patient history simultaneously.

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:35.100
That's extraordinarily powerful. It's also where the validation problem
becomes orders of magnitude harder.

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:41.700
How do you build a ground truth dataset for a model that operates
across five specialties and four data modalities?

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:48.200
Short answer: you don't. Not cleanly.
You build approximations, and you're transparent about their limits.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:54.800
Let's talk about diagnostic AI specifically.
The benchmark everyone cites is the Stanford CheXNet paper from 2017.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:01.300
A CNN trained on 100,000 chest X-rays outperformed
the average radiologist on pneumonia detection.

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:07.900
That headline traveled fast. What traveled less fast was the methodology critique
published six months later by Oakden-Rayner and colleagues.

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:14.400
The comparison was against radiologists operating under artificial constraints —
time pressure, no clinical context, no prior imaging.

00:02:14.600 --> 00:02:20.800
In real clinical conditions, with access to patient history and prior scans,
the performance gap largely disappeared.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.300
This is a pattern you will see repeatedly in this field.
Benchmark performance and clinical performance are not the same thing.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:33.900
Distribution shift is probably the single most important concept
for anyone working on deployed medical AI.

00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:40.400
A model trained at a well-resourced urban academic medical center
will see a very different data distribution than a rural clinic in Mississippi.

00:02:40.600 --> 00:02:46.900
Different scanner manufacturers. Different patient demographics.
Different prevalence rates for the same conditions.

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:53.400
A model that performs at 94% AUC in your training environment
might degrade to 81% in deployment. That delta has clinical consequences.

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:59.800
I want to shift now to a domain where AI has had unambiguous,
well-documented positive impact: pathology.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:06.300
Whole slide imaging combined with deep learning has transformed
how we approach cancer grading — particularly in prostate and breast cancer.

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:12.700
Gleason grading of prostate cancer is famously subjective.
Inter-observer agreement among expert pathologists is around 60 to 70 percent.

00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:19.100
AI systems trained on large annotated slide libraries
have demonstrated agreement rates above 85% against expert consensus panels.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:25.600
That's not replacing the pathologist.
That's giving every pathologist access to a second opinion grounded in thousands of cases.

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:32.100
The workflow integration question is where most implementations fail.
And I want to be honest with you about this.

00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:38.500
You can build a technically excellent model and watch it gather dust
because it adds three clicks to an already overloaded clinical workflow.

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:44.900
Clinician adoption is a UX problem as much as an AI problem.
The best model in the world is useless if no one runs it.

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:51.400
I spent two years on an implementation project at UCSF.
We had a sepsis prediction model with genuinely strong performance metrics.

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:57.800
Alert fatigue killed it. Nurses were receiving 40-plus alerts per shift.
The sepsis alert became noise. Actionability collapsed.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.200
We rebuilt the interface. Reduced alert volume by 60% through better thresholding.
Adoption recovered. Outcomes improved. Same model.

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:10.700
The lesson: deployment is a sociotechnical problem,
not a technical problem with some social considerations bolted on.

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:17.100
Now I want to address the equity dimension directly,
because it's often treated as a footnote and it should be a headline.

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:23.500
The 2019 Obermeyer et al. study in Science is required reading for this course.
If you haven't read it, read it this week.

00:04:23.700 --> 00:04:29.900
They analyzed a widely deployed commercial algorithm used to allocate
care management resources to high-risk patients.

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:36.300
The algorithm used healthcare cost as a proxy for health need.
Black patients, at the same level of illness, generated lower costs.

00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:42.700
Why? Systemic underutilization of healthcare due to access barriers,
historical mistrust, economic constraints.

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:49.100
The model learned the bias baked into the training data.
It then systematically under-referred Black patients for care management.

00:04:49.300 --> 00:04:55.500
At scale. Across hundreds of hospitals. For years.
Before anyone caught it.

00:04:55.700 --> 00:05:01.900
This is not a hypothetical. This is not a thought experiment.
This happened. It is documented. It is a warning.

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:08.300
Proxy variables are one of the most dangerous failure modes in applied ML,
and healthcare is saturated with them.

00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:14.700
Any time you use a downstream outcome as a label —
readmission, cost, length of stay — ask what that outcome is a proxy for.

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:21.000
And ask who is underrepresented in the historical data
that generated those outcomes.

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:27.400
Let me close this section with something more optimistic:
large language models in clinical documentation.

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:33.800
Ambient AI scribes — models that listen to a patient encounter
and generate a structured clinical note — are in active deployment right now.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:40.200
Nuance DAX, Suki, Abridge. Clinicians using these tools
report saving 60 to 90 minutes of documentation time per day.

00:05:40.400 --> 00:05:46.600
That is time returned to patient care.
That is a direct, measurable reduction in burnout vector.

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:53.000
The accuracy challenges are real — hallucination in a clinical note
is a patient safety issue, not just an inconvenience.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:59.400
But the human-in-the-loop model here is natural.
The clinician reviews and signs the note. The AI drafts. The human audits.

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:05.800
That's a workflow that maps well to how trust in AI-assisted systems
should be built incrementally.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.500
We'll pick up after the break with drug discovery and genomics.
Questions so far? Yes — go ahead.